const tours = [{"name":"Bug #13399: Form default prefill corrupts model_fields_set","color":"#ff4466","keywords":["params.Form","routing.get_request_handler","utils.request_body_to_args","utils._extract_form_body","utils._get_multidict_value","deepcopy","utils._validate_value_with_model_field","get_cached_model_fields","model_fields_set","_get_multidict_value","_extract_form_body","request_body_to_args","_validate_value_with_model_field","Form","BaseModel","FormData"],"steps":[{"text":"<strong class='tc'>Form</strong> is a subclass of <strong class='tc'>Body</strong> (which is a subclass of FieldInfo). When a user annotates a parameter as Annotated[ExampleModel, Form()], FastAPI treats the <strong class='tc'>BaseModel</strong> as a form-encoded body rather than a JSON body. This is where the two code paths diverge.","node":"params.Form"},{"text":"In <strong class='tc'>get_request_handler</strong> (<strong class='tc'>routing</strong>.py ~line 371), is_body_form is set to True when body_field.field_info is an instance of <strong class='tc'>params.Form</strong>. This determines whether the request body is <strong class='tc'>read</strong> as <strong class='tc'>FormData</strong> (<strong class='tc'>request.form</strong>()) or JSON (<strong class='tc'>request.json</strong>()). For <strong class='tc'>Form</strong> <strong class='tc'>models</strong>, body becomes a FormData multidict object.","node":"routing.get_request_handler"},{"text":"<strong class='tc'>request_body_to_args</strong> receives the <strong class='tc'>FormData</strong> as received_body. For a single non-embedded <strong class='tc'>BaseModel</strong> <strong class='tc'>Form</strong> field, it extracts the model's individual fields via <strong class='tc'>get_cached_model_fields</strong> (line 970), then passes the FormData to <strong class='tc'>_extract_form_body</strong> (line 973). This is the critical branching point: JSON data arrives as a plain dict with only user-supplied <strong class='tc'>keys</strong>, but form data goes through field-by-field extraction.","node":"utils.request_body_to_args"},{"text":"THE KEY FUNCTION. <strong class='tc'>_extract_form_body</strong> iterates over every field in the model (line 918) and calls <strong class='tc'>_get_multidict_value</strong> for each one. It builds a dict of field_alias -> value. If _get_multidict_value returns a non-None value (including a prefilled default), it is added to the dict. This means the dict sent to Pydantic validation will contain default <strong class='tc'>values</strong> for fields the user never submitted.","node":"utils._extract_form_body"},{"text":"ROOT CAUSE. When a field's value is None (not present in form data), empty string, or empty sequence, this function checks <strong class='tc'>field.field_info.is_required</strong>() (line 777). If the field is NOT required, it returns <strong class='tc'>deepcopy</strong>(field.default) (line 780). This pre-fills the default value AS IF the user had submitted it. For JSON bodies this function is never called \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the JSON dict simply omits missing <strong class='tc'>keys</strong>, and Pydantic handles defaults internally while correctly tracking which fields were set.","node":"utils._get_multidict_value"},{"text":"<strong class='tc'>deepcopy</strong>(field.default) at line 780 returns a concrete default value (e.g., True for field_1: <strong class='tc'>bool</strong> = True). This value is indistinguishable from a user-submitted value once it enters the dict. The <strong class='tc'>copy</strong> is defensive (prevents mutation of the field's default), but the real problem is that any value is returned at all \u00e2\u20ac\u201d it should return nothing and let Pydantic fill in the default.","node":"deepcopy"},{"text":"Back in <strong class='tc'>request_body_to_args</strong>, the pre-filled dict (with default <strong class='tc'>values</strong> injected) is passed to <strong class='tc'>_validate_value_with_model_field</strong> as the 'value' argument (line 977). Since value is not None (it contains the prefilled defaults), validation proceeds normally via <strong class='tc'>field.validate</strong>() \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Pydantic instantiates the model with all fields 'present' and marks them all as explicitly set in <strong class='tc'>model_fields_set</strong>.","node":"utils._validate_value_with_model_field"},{"text":"<strong class='tc'>get_cached_model_fields</strong> (in <strong class='tc'>_compat</strong>/v2.py) extracts <strong class='tc'>ModelField</strong> objects from the <strong class='tc'>BaseModel</strong>'s model_fields. Each ModelField wraps a FieldInfo with its name, annotation, and default. These fields drive the iteration in <strong class='tc'>_extract_form_body</strong> \u00e2\u20ac\u201d every field in the model is visited, not just the ones present in the form submission.","node":"get_cached_model_fields"},{"text":"SYMPTOM. Pydantic's <strong class='tc'>model_fields_set</strong> tracks which fields were explicitly provided during model construction. For JSON body (POST /body with {}), the model receives an empty dict, Pydantic fills defaults internally, and model_fields_set = set(). For <strong class='tc'>Form</strong> body (POST /form with empty data), the model receives {'field_1': True} (prefilled), Pydantic sees field_1 as user-provided, and model_fields_set = {'field_1'}. This breaks any logic that depends on distinguishing user-set vs default <strong class='tc'>values</strong>.","node":"model_fields_set"}]},{"name":"Bug #13399: JSON body vs Form body \u00e2\u20ac\u201d why they differ","color":"#00d4ff","keywords":["routing.get_request_handler","utils.solve_dependencies","utils.request_body_to_args","utils._extract_form_body","utils._validate_value_with_model_field","utils._get_multidict_value","utils.request_params_to_args","request_body_to_args","_extract_form_body","_get_multidict_value","FormData","request.form","request.json","body_to_process","deepcopy"],"steps":[{"text":"BRANCH POINT. is_body_form = <strong class='tc'>isinstance</strong>(body_field.field_info, <strong class='tc'>params.Form</strong>) at line 371. If True, body = await <strong class='tc'>request.form</strong>() returns a <strong class='tc'>FormData</strong> (Starlette multidict). If False, body = await <strong class='tc'>request.json</strong>() returns a plain dict. This is the first divergence \u00e2\u20ac\u201d FormData is a multidict keyed only by actually-submitted fields; a JSON dict is also keyed only by submitted fields. At this point, both representations are correct.","node":"routing.get_request_handler"},{"text":"<strong class='tc'>solve_dependencies</strong> passes the body (<strong class='tc'>FormData</strong> or dict) unchanged to <strong class='tc'>request_body_to_args</strong> at line 706. The body has not been modified yet \u00e2\u20ac\u201d it still contains only what the user actually submitted.","node":"utils.solve_dependencies"},{"text":"SECOND BRANCH POINT. <strong class='tc'>isinstance</strong>(received_body, <strong class='tc'>FormData</strong>) at line 968. If True (form), fields_to_extract is populated from the <strong class='tc'>BaseModel</strong> via <strong class='tc'>get_cached_model_fields</strong> (line 970) and <strong class='tc'>body_to_process</strong> is overwritten by <strong class='tc'>_extract_form_body</strong> (line 973) \u00e2\u20ac\u201d this is where defaults get injected. If False (JSON), body_to_process stays as the original JSON dict with only user-provided <strong class='tc'>keys</strong>.","node":"utils.request_body_to_args"},{"text":"FORM PATH ONLY. Iterates every field in the model and calls <strong class='tc'>_get_multidict_value</strong> for each one (line 919). For missing fields, _get_multidict_value returns <strong class='tc'>deepcopy</strong>(field.default). The resulting dict contains ALL fields \u00e2\u20ac\u201d both user-submitted and default-prefilled \u00e2\u20ac\u201d with no way to distinguish them. This dict replaces <strong class='tc'>body_to_process</strong>.","node":"utils._extract_form_body"},{"text":"CONVERGENCE POINT. Both JSON and <strong class='tc'>Form</strong> paths reach <strong class='tc'>_validate_value_with_model_field</strong> (line 977 for single-field, line 991 for multi-field). JSON path: value is a dict with only user-submitted <strong class='tc'>keys</strong> \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Pydantic fills defaults internally \u00e2\u2020\u2019 model_fields_set correct. Form path: value is a dict with ALL keys (including prefilled defaults) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Pydantic sees them all as user-provided \u00e2\u2020\u2019 model_fields_set wrong.","node":"utils._validate_value_with_model_field"},{"text":"FIX LOCATION. Lines 777-780: when value is missing and field is not required, return <strong class='tc'>deepcopy</strong>(field.default). PR #13464 proposes removing this return and instead returning None (bare return), letting Pydantic handle the default value assignment. This makes the <strong class='tc'>Form</strong> path behave like the JSON path \u00e2\u20ac\u201d only explicitly submitted <strong class='tc'>values</strong> reach the model constructor.","node":"utils._get_multidict_value"},{"text":"SECONDARY EFFECT. <strong class='tc'>_extract_form_body</strong> only adds <strong class='tc'>values</strong> to the result dict when value is not None (line 938: 'if value is not None'). If <strong class='tc'>_get_multidict_value</strong> returns None instead of the default, missing-but-optional fields will be omitted from the dict entirely \u00e2\u20ac\u201d which is exactly what happens in the JSON path. Pydantic then fills in defaults and correctly excludes them from model_fields_set.","node":"utils._extract_form_body"},{"text":"RELATED CONCERN. <strong class='tc'>request_params_to_args</strong> (query/header/cookie <strong class='tc'>params</strong>) also calls <strong class='tc'>_get_multidict_value</strong> (line 825, 853) with the same default-prefilling behavior. The fix to _get_multidict_value would also affect these param <strong class='tc'>types</strong>. However, for non-body params, the validation flow is different (individual fields, not a full <strong class='tc'>BaseModel</strong>), so the impact differs.","node":"utils.request_params_to_args"}]}];
